Mexico's minister of energy andmines, Alfredo del Mazo, has yet to reply to a Peruvianinvitation for ministerial-level talks on bilateral cooperationin silver marketing, a ministry spokesman said.    Peruvian officials said they extended the invitationearlier this week and that it was possible the talks could beheld within the next 15 days.    Meanwhile, a Banco de Mexico spokesman confirmed thatMexican central bank head Miguel Mancera Aguayo held privatetalks here yesterday with the president of the Peruvian centralbank.    The spokesman said the talks were in line with mutualconsultation agreements made during Peruvian President AlanGarcia's visit to Mexico in march.    Press reports citing diplomatic sources at the meeting saidthe two central bank heads discussed means of coordinatingactions in the silver market.    Mexico is the world's leading silver produer. It producedabout 73.9 mln troy ounces in 1986, according to preliminarygovernment figures.    Peru, the second biggest producer of the precious metal,earlier this week froze new silver sales in an effort tostabilize silver prices. It produced 57 mln troy ounces in1986. Reuter&#3;